# TODO

- `truthvalue` (`false`, `ambiguous`, `true`)
- `real` (arbitrary precision)
- `string`
- Lattices: Replace types with value-sets
  - enumerated (one or more distinct values)
  - ranges (minimum and inclusive or exclusive maximum)
  - length and regex matches for `string`
  - Runtime: use simple C types when range and precision allow
  - Static code-path analysis: Variables and expressions are compatible based on value-set
  - `subset boolean = truthvalue @except(ambiguous)` or `subset boolean = truthvalue @values(false, true)`
  - `subset natural = integer @range(0...)`
- `data`, `object` and `service` types
  - Heap allocated and reference counted
  - `data` is a naked data structure — no methods
  - `object` is encapsulated data — only accessed through methods
  - `service` is like `object` but not restricted to its own heap memory
- Validation: primitive values cannot be assigned to `ref` variables
- Validation: `service` type cannot be assigned to `const`/`mut` variables
- `trait` applicable to data-oriented type (i.e. `data` and `object`)
- `role` applicable to `service` (`ref` only)

## Clearly advanced (and maybe entirely out of scope)

- Referential constraints such as `func add(a: integer, b: integer) -> integer @value(a+b)`
- Staggered lattices `integer @range(1...10) \/ @range(55...100)` (where `\/` means union or join)
- Optimise the AST code based on known value-sets
